# Time series examples. Choose Gaussian white noise to compare with. Use the same length.
np.random.seed()
simulated_noise_data = np.random.randn(T1)
simulated_noise_data = np.array(simulated_noise_data - simulated_noise_data.mean())
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 7.5]); # Set size for the figure
plt.plot(simulated_noise_data)
plt.title("Simulated noise data")
plt.show()
In [9]:
# Perform fast Fourier Transform of the Gaussian white noise time series

x = np.linspace(1., T1, T1, endpoint=False)

noise_dataf = np.fft.fft(simulated_noise_data)
xf = np.fft.fftfreq(T1, 1)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(xf[:T1//2], noise_dataf[:T1//2])
# plt.grid()
plt.show()
In [10]:
# Show the power spectral density of the Gaussian white noise time series in linear and semilog plot
f, Pxx_den = signal.periodogram(simulated_noise_data, 1)
plt.plot(f, Pxx_den)
plt.xlabel('frequency [Hz]')
plt.ylabel('PSD [V**2/Hz] (linear)')
plt.show()
plt.semilogy(f, Pxx_den)
plt.ylim([1e-7, 1e2])
plt.xlabel('frequency [Hz]')
plt.ylabel('PSD [V**2/Hz] (semilog)')
plt.show()
In [11]:
# Find the autocorrelation function of the Gaussian white noise time series and its absolute value
noise_acf = acf(simulated_noise_data)
noise_acf_f = np.fft.fft(noise_acf)
x_acf = np.linspace(1, len(noise_acf), len(noise_acf))
x_acf_f = np.fft.fftfreq(len(noise_acf), 1)
plot_acf(simulated_noise_data)
plt.show()
plot_acf(np.abs(simulated_noise_data))
plt.show()

In [25]:
# Generate a Brownian random walk time series and make a plot
N_steps = 500000
brownian = random_walk(N_steps, proba=0.5)
plt.plot(brownian)
plt.show()

# Compute the Hurst exponent of a Brownian random walk time series
start_time = time.time()
H, c, val = compute_Hc(brownian)
print("Total time to compute the Hurst exponent", "%s seconds" % round(time.time() - start_time, 10))
print("Hurst exponent = {:.5f}".format(H))

Total time to compute the Hurst exponent 3.9634063244 seconds
Hurst exponent = 0.50924
